        "old_string": "{\n  \"buggy_files\": [\"fs/nfs/nfs3proc.c\"],\n  \"buggy_functions\": [\"nfs3_rpc_wrapper\"],\n  \"confidence\": 0.85,\n  \"reasoning\": \"The nfs3_rpc_wrapper function (lines 30-42) is a wrapper around rpc_call_sync that handles -EJUKEBOX errors by retrying after a sleep. The bug is on line 39 where the code unconditionally sets 'res = -ERESTARTSYS' after calling freezable_schedule_timeout_killable_unsafe() without checking the return value. This return value indicates whether the sleep was interrupted by a signal. When the sleep completes normally (no signal), res should remain -EJUKEBOX to allow the loop to retry the RPC call. Instead, the code unconditionally converts it to -ERESTARTSYS, which causes nfs_revalidate_inode to treat this as a permanent failure. This leads to inode invalidation even though the server may have successfully replied with the attributes. The tcpdump evidence in the bug report shows the server did reply, but the client incorrectly reports -512 (ERESTARTSYS) due to this race condition in the retry logic. The fix should check the return value of freezable_schedule_timeout_killable_unsafe and only set res = -ERESTARTSYS if a signal actually occurred.\"\n}",
        "new_string": "{\n  \"buggy_files\": [\"fs/nfs/inode.c\", \"fs/nfs/dir.c\"],\n  \"buggy_functions\": [\"__nfs_revalidate_inode\", \"nfs_lookup_verify_inode\"],\n  \"confidence\": 0.82,\n  \"reasoning\": \"The bug is a failure to properly handle the -ERESTARTSYS (signal interrupted) error in the inode revalidation path. When an RPC getattr call is interrupted by a signal, it returns -ERESTARTSYS. In __nfs_revalidate_inode (fs/nfs/inode.c:960-971), this error is treated the same as other permanent errors - the function returns the error code without any special handling for this transient signal-based error. This error then propagates to nfs_lookup_verify_inode (fs/nfs/dir.c:1073-1075), which returns it to nfs_lookup_revalidate, causing the dentry to be invalidated even though the inode itself is still valid. The tcpdump evidence shows the server DID reply successfully, but the client task was interrupted by a signal before the reply could be fully processed and incorporated. The fix should treat -ERESTARTSYS as a transient, recoverable error: either retry the getattr call, or don't invalidate the inode/dentry when this error occurs. The root cause is that between kernels 3.14 and 4.1, the RPC/signal interaction changed such that signals can now interrupt getattr calls that previously wouldn't have been interrupted, exposing this missing error handling.\"\n}",
        "replace_all": false
