        "new_string": "{\n  \"buggy_files\": [\"fs/nfs/inode.c\"],\n  \"buggy_functions\": [\"__nfs_revalidate_inode\"],\n  \"confidence\": 0.85,\n  \"reasoning\": \"The bug is in __nfs_revalidate_inode (fs/nfs/inode.c, lines 960-971) which fails to properly handle the -ERESTARTSYS error returned from NFS_PROTO(inode)->getattr(). When an RPC getattr call is interrupted by a signal, it returns -ERESTARTSYS, which is a transient/recoverable error indicating 'try again' rather than a permanent failure. Currently, any non-zero status from getattr (lines 961-971) except -ESTALE is treated as a permanent error and returned to the caller, causing dentry invalidation in nfs_lookup_revalidate. This is incorrect for signal interruptions. The fix should add special handling for -ERESTARTSYS similar to -ESTALE: either retry the getattr or return 0 to indicate the inode remains valid despite the transient error. The tcpdump evidence in the bug report shows the server replied successfully, but the client task was interrupted by a signal before fully processing the reply. Between kernel 3.14 and 4.1, changes to RPC signal handling made this race condition more likely, exposing the missing error handling.\"\n}",
